    <h1>9 POP-ROCK RE-CODE&#xD;&#xA;CNBlue</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201210/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-10"><time>2020-12-10</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>The South Korean band CNBlue make their long-awaited re­turn as a three-piece group af­ter a har­row­ing 2019.</p>
    <p>Mem­ber Lee Jong-hyun left the group when he ad­mit­ted to view­ing sex videos of women taken with­out their con­sent, which were shared by dis­graced singer Jung Joon-young.</p>
    <p>CNBlue’s lat­est al­bum leads with the track Then, Now And For­ever – an uplift­ing lis­ten which seems to ad­dress the group’s past woes as the lyrics go: “There will be bet­ter days/We’re here then, now and for­ever.”</p>

